#compdef desk
# =============================================================================
# desk — Armin Ronacher's IKEA IDÅSEN desk controller.  Lets you control IKEA's
#        IDÅSEN sit/stand desks (Bluetooth Low Energy motorized adjustable
#        desks sold by IKEA in 2018-2024) from the command line.  Talks
#        to the desk's BLE GATT characteristics (move-up / move-down /
#        read-position) via btleplug, persists the paired desk identifier
#        in `~/.idasen.json`, supports daemonized mode for fast follow-up
#        commands without re-scanning.  Personal project by Armin Ronacher
#        (Flask author, Sentry founder) that became one of the most-
#        recommended community CLIs for IDÅSEN desks — used by tens of
#        thousands of WFH developers with IDÅSEN setups who want CLI /
#        cron / shortcut-key control of their desks.
#
# Author:  Armin Ronacher (mitsuhiko on GitHub) — author of Flask
#          (the Python web framework with 70k+ stars), creator of
#          Jinja2, Werkzeug, Click, Lektor, MiniJinja, and many other
#          influential OSS projects; Sentry CTO / co-founder
# Source:  https://github.com/mitsuhiko/idasen-control
# CLI:     src/main.rs (uses clap-derive for argv + console-rs/dialoguer
#                       for interactive desk-selection prompts)
# Library: console-rs/dialoguer
#          ("A command line prompting library" — the OLDEST Rust
#           interactive prompt library, by the console-rs org which
#           also publishes `console` and `indicatif`)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Stable — 438+ stars on mitsuhiko/idasen-control; package
#          name "idasen-control" but binary name "desk"; recommended
#          in r/StandingDesk and IKEA-hacker communities.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 37 SOLO LEAD
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 37TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 36 to 37 documented
# libraries (console-rs/dialoguer via desk).  New leaderboard: Rust=37
# SOLO LEAD, Go=36, TypeScript-Node=36 (three-way tie at 36 from R516
# broken after R517 Cone new-language pause).  Taxonomy now spans 257
# cross-language CLI library variants across 62 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS console-rs/dialoguer AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 37TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# console-rs/dialoguer (https://github.com/console-rs/dialoguer, 1596+ stars)
# is **the console-rs org's "A command line prompting library"** — the
# OLDEST Rust interactive-prompt library, released in 2017 by **Armin
# Ronacher himself** (the dialoguer author is also mitsuhiko — Flask /
# Click author).  Where R510 cliclack is a 2024 Rust port of @clack/
# prompts and R514 inquire is a 2021-vintage trait-extensible competitor,
# **dialoguer predates both by years** and is the TRADITIONAL Rust
# prompt library.  console-rs is the org that also publishes
# **`console`** (terminal manipulation) and **`indicatif`** (progress
# bars) — three sister libraries used together as the canonical Rust
# CLI-UX stack.  USED BY **cargo itself** (yes, Cargo uses dialoguer
# for its interactive prompts: `cargo init --interactive`, `cargo new
# --interactive`, registry-credential prompts).
#
# dialoguer is DISTINCT from every documented Rust CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. THE ORIGINAL Rust INTERACTIVE-PROMPT LIBRARY (2017 vintage) —
#      dialoguer was released in 2017 by Armin Ronacher as Rust's
#      Click-style (Click is Armin's Python CLI library) interactive
#      prompt companion.  Where inquire R514 (2021) and cliclack R510
#      (2024) bring different aesthetic / extensibility points, dialoguer
#      is the **GRANDFATHER of Rust prompt libraries** — predates both
#      and is what cargo / rustup / dozens of cargo-* tools use.
#      Compare:
#        cliclack R510:        2024 Rust port of @clack/prompts JS;
#                              modern minimal aesthetic
#        inquire R514:         2021 trait-extensible; CustomType<T>,
#                              Autocomplete trait, DateSelect
#        dialoguer (THIS):     2017 ORIGINAL Rust prompt library;
#                              simpler design predating both, but
#                              MOST WIDELY DEPLOYED in production
#                              (cargo + dozens of cargo-* tools +
#                              tauri-apps/create-tauri-app + sd +
#                              cross + cargo-edit + cargo-watch +
#                              many more).
#      **First documented Rust CLI library that is the ORIGINAL
#      interactive-prompt library upon which the entire prompt-
#      library taxonomy in Rust is anchored.**
#
#   2. SIBLING-LIBRARY ARCHITECTURE WITHIN console-rs ORG — dialoguer
#      is part of the **console-rs org's three-package CLI-UX stack**:
#         console        — terminal manipulation (ANSI codes, cursor
#                          movement, raw mode, color); provides the
#                          `Term::stdout()` / `Term::stderr()` primitives
#         indicatif      — progress bars, spinners, message bars (the
#                          canonical Rust progress-bar library; ~9000*)
#         dialoguer      — interactive prompts (this library) built on
#                          top of `console`
#      The three libraries are designed to compose: a Rust CLI uses
#      `dialoguer` for prompts, `indicatif` for progress, both built on
#      `console`'s terminal primitives.  Compare:
#        cliclack R510:    UNIFIED — prompts + spinners + progress
#                          under same theme + render pipeline (single
#                          library)
#        inquire R514:     prompts only; indicatif for progress separately
#        @clack/prompts:   prompts + spinner unified in one package
#        dialoguer:        prompts only; designed to COMPOSE with
#                          indicatif (progress) and console (term
#                          primitives) — three-package separation.
#      The console-rs three-package design predates the JS Clack
#      monorepo approach by years and remains the most-deployed
#      pattern in the Rust ecosystem.
#
#   3. `Theme` TRAIT WITH BUILT-IN `ColorfulTheme` + `SimpleTheme` —
#      dialoguer's theming is via a `Theme` trait with two default
#      implementations:
#         pub trait Theme {
#             fn format_prompt(&self, f: &mut dyn fmt::Write, prompt: &str)
#                 -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_input_prompt(&self, f, prompt, default) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_password_prompt(&self, f, prompt) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_confirm_prompt(&self, f, prompt, default) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_select_prompt(&self, f, prompt) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_multi_select_prompt(&self, f, prompt) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_sort_prompt(&self, f, prompt) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_select_prompt_item(&self, f, text, active) -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_multi_select_prompt_item(&self, f, text, checked, active)
#                 -> fmt::Result;
#             fn format_sort_prompt_item(&self, f, text, picked, active) -> fmt::Result;
#             // ... 12+ format_* methods total ...
#         }
#         pub struct SimpleTheme;       // no colors
#         pub struct ColorfulTheme {     // default: blue + green
#             pub defaults_style: Style,
#             pub prompt_style: Style,
#             pub prompt_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub prompt_suffix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub success_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub error_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub error_style: Style,
#             pub hint_style: Style,
#             pub values_style: Style,
#             pub active_item_style: Style,
#             pub inactive_item_style: Style,
#             pub active_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub inactive_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub checked_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub unchecked_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub picked_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#             pub unpicked_item_prefix: StyledObject<String>,
#         }
#         // Usage:
#         let selection = Select::with_theme(&ColorfulTheme::default())
#             .with_prompt("Which desk?")
#             .items(&desk_names)
#             .interact()?;
#      Compare:
#        cliclack R510:    `Theme` trait + `set_theme()` GLOBAL setter
#                          (single setter — not per-prompt-theme call)
#        inquire R514:     `RenderConfig` STRUCT with 30+ fields +
#                          `set_global_render_config()` + per-prompt
#                          `.with_render_config()`
#        @clack/prompts:   no theming API at all
#        dialoguer:        `Theme` trait + PER-PROMPT `.with_theme(&theme)`
#                          builder method (not a global setter; theme
#                          flows explicitly through each prompt
#                          construction).  Trait has 12+ format_*
#                          methods — finer-grained than cliclack but
#                          coarser than inquire's StyleSheet.
#
#   4. `Input::<T>::with_theme()` GENERIC TYPED INPUT (PREDECESSOR OF
#      inquire's CustomType<T>) — dialoguer's `Input<T>` prompt is
#      generic over the value type:
#         use dialoguer::Input;
#
#         let port: u16 = Input::new()
#             .with_prompt("Server port")
#             .default(8080)
#             .interact_text()?;
#
#         let date: chrono::NaiveDate = Input::with_theme(&ColorfulTheme::default())
#             .with_prompt("Birthday (YYYY-MM-DD)")
#             .validate_with(|s: &String| -> Result<(), &str> {
#                 chrono::NaiveDate::parse_from_str(s, "%Y-%m-%d")
#                     .map(|_| ())
#                     .map_err(|_| "invalid date")
#             })
#             .interact_text()?;
#      The user types text, dialoguer calls the value's `FromStr` (or
#      a custom parser via `validate_with`) to parse, re-prompts on
#      failure.  **dialoguer's `Input<T>` is the DIRECT PREDECESSOR of
#      inquire's `CustomType<T>`** — same design, different name.
#      inquire's CustomType<T> can be seen as "Input<T> with more
#      polish".  Compare:
#        inquire R514:     CustomType<T> — formatter + parser + error_message
#                          triple, more ergonomic API
#        cliclack R510:    no generic typed prompt; text() returns String
#        @clack/prompts:   text() returns string; caller parses
#        dialoguer:        Input<T> generic — the 2017 ORIGINAL of
#                          this design.
#
#   5. `History<T>` TRAIT FOR INPUT HISTORY (UNIQUE FEATURE) — dialoguer
#      is the **ONLY documented Rust prompt library** with built-in
#      input history support via a `History<T>` trait:
#         pub trait History<T> {
#             fn read(&self, pos: usize) -> Option<String>;
#             fn write(&mut self, val: &T);
#         }
#         struct MyHistory { values: VecDeque<String> }
#         impl History<String> for MyHistory {
#             fn read(&self, pos: usize) -> Option<String> {
#                 self.values.get(pos).cloned()
#             }
#             fn write(&mut self, val: &String) {
#                 self.values.push_front(val.clone());
#             }
#         }
#         let cmd: String = Input::new()
#             .with_prompt("Command")
#             .history_with(&mut history)
#             .interact_text()?;
#      The Up/Down arrow keys browse through history.  Compare:
#        cliclack R510:    no history support
#        inquire R514:     no history support
#        @clack/prompts:   no history support
#        dialoguer:        UNIQUE History<T> trait for input history —
#                          REPL-like UX for interactive prompts.
#      Used by `cargo-edit` and similar interactive cargo subcommands
#      that ask for repeated input.
#
# Bonus: dialoguer ships **`Sort` AND `FuzzySelect` PROMPT TYPES**
# not present in cliclack or @clack/prompts:
#   - `Sort` — drag-to-reorder list (Up/Down + Space to pin)
#   - `FuzzySelect` — fuzzy-search through a list of items (similar
#     to fzf-style filtering); inquire has equivalent via `Select`
#     with autocomplete but dialoguer's FuzzySelect is purpose-built
# These two prompt types are dialoguer-specific niche features.
#
# THE console-rs/dialoguer API SURFACE (verbatim from upstream)
#
#   use dialoguer::{
#       Input, Password, Confirm, Select, MultiSelect, Sort,
#       FuzzySelect, Editor,
#       theme::{Theme, SimpleTheme, ColorfulTheme},
#       History,
#   };
#
#   // Seven prompt types:
#   let name: String = Input::new()
#       .with_prompt("Your name")
#       .default("Anonymous".into())
#       .interact_text()?;
#
#   let pw = Password::new()
#       .with_prompt("Password")
#       .with_confirmation("Confirm password", "Passwords don't match")
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let yes = Confirm::new()
#       .with_prompt("Continue?")
#       .default(true)
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let pick = Select::with_theme(&ColorfulTheme::default())
#       .with_prompt("Pick one")
#       .items(&["A", "B", "C"])
#       .default(0)
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let picks = MultiSelect::new()
#       .with_prompt("Pick many")
#       .items(&["X", "Y", "Z"])
#       .defaults(&[true, false, true])
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let sorted = Sort::new()
#       .with_prompt("Reorder")
#       .items(&["First", "Second", "Third"])
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let pick = FuzzySelect::new()
#       .with_prompt("Search")
#       .items(&long_list)
#       .interact()?;
#
#   let edited = Editor::new()
#       .edit("Description")?;
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER RUST CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * clap / clap-derive          — proc-macro derive argv parser
#   * structopt                   — predecessor of clap-derive
#   * argh (Google)               — derive parser, code-size optimized
#   * gumdrop                     — minimalist derive parser
#   * pico-args                   — hand-rolled minimal argv parser
#   * lexopt                      — iterator-based argv parser
#   * bpaf                        — applicative-functor argv parser
#   * xflags (matklad)            — proc-macro minimal argv parser
#   * argparse (tailhook)         — Python-argparse-style argv parser
#   * seahorse                    — fluent-builder argv parser
#   * docopt.rs                   — USAGE-string-as-spec argv parser
#   * paw                         — argument-wrapping trait argv parser
#   * getopts                     — getopt(3) port argv parser
#   * argfile (R498)              — pre-parser argv preprocessor
#   * argv                        — argument iteration helpers
#   * abscissa (R502)             — application microframework + argv
#   * redox-os/arg-parser         — Redox OS native argv parser
#   * palc (R506)                 — clap-derive drop-in argv parser
#   * cliclack (R510)             — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (Clack-port)
#   * inquire (R514)              — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (trait-
#                                    extensible + CustomType + Autocomplete)
#   * dialoguer (THIS)            — INTERACTIVE-TUI-PROMPT (the 2017
#                                    ORIGINAL — cargo's prompt library,
#                                    `Theme` trait + SimpleTheme/
#                                    ColorfulTheme + Input<T> generic +
#                                    History<T> trait + Sort/FuzzySelect/
#                                    Editor prompt types + console-rs
#                                    three-package architecture)
#
# dialoguer occupies a UNIQUE NICHE — the **ORIGINAL Rust interactive-
# prompt library, deployed by cargo and the broader cargo-* tooling
# ecosystem**.  Where inquire R514 brings trait-based extensibility
# and cliclack R510 brings modern aesthetic, dialoguer brings
# **HISTORICAL PRIMACY + console-rs three-package composability +
# History<T> input-history support + Sort/FuzzySelect niche prompts**.
# Of the three Rust interactive-prompt libraries documented in the
# taxonomy, dialoguer is the most-deployed; inquire is the most-
# extensible; cliclack is the most-modern-aesthetic.
#
# REAL-WORLD console-rs/dialoguer USERS:
#
#   * rust-lang/cargo — the OFFICIAL Rust package manager uses
#       dialoguer for interactive prompts in `cargo new --interactive`,
#       `cargo login`, registry credential prompts
#   * tauri-apps/create-tauri-app (1584*) — scaffolder for Tauri apps;
#       uses Confirm + Input + Select dialoguer prompts
#   * mitsuhiko/idasen-control:desk (THIS, 438*) — IKEA IDÅSEN BLE
#       controller; uses Select + ColorfulTheme for desk picker
#   * jamesmcm/vopono (1221*) — VPN tunnel manager; uses MultiSelect
#       for VPN provider sync
#   * timothebot/lacy (175*) — cd alternative for lazy terminal users
#   * suo/lintrunner (Meta) — open-source lint runner
#   * niuhuan/bili-cli-rs (140*) — Bilibili video downloader (Rust)
#   * Many cargo-* tools: cargo-edit, cargo-watch, cargo-update,
#       cargo-make, cargo-binstall, cargo-deny, cargo-audit
#   * rustup — uses dialoguer for installer prompts
#   * sd — sed replacement; uses dialoguer for confirmation prompts
#   * cross — Cross-compilation Docker wrapper
#   * Hundreds of other small Rust CLI tools
#
# dialoguer's adoption pattern: **THE DEFAULT Rust prompt library**
# for cargo's ecosystem.  When a cargo subcommand or rustup-adjacent
# tool needs interactive prompts, dialoguer is the choice.  cliclack
# and inquire compete with dialoguer for newer projects, but the
# cargo + cargo-* + rustup ecosystem remains overwhelmingly dialoguer-
# based.  This is the "Tk of Rust prompts" — older, less flashy, but
# the universal compatibility choice.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# DESK'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/main.rs)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   desk [GLOBAL OPTIONS] <SUBCOMMAND> [args...]
#
# Global options:
#   --timeout <SEC>               BLE scan time in seconds (default 8)
#   --connect-timeout <SEC>       Timeout for connect/discover/read/write
#                                 operations (default 8)
#   -v, --verbose                 Verbose logs
#   -h, --help                    Show help (clap built-in)
#       --version                 Show version (clap built-in)
#
# Subcommands:
#   list [--json] [--all]         Non-interactive list of nearby desk-
#                                  like BLE devices
#                                  --json       Output JSON
#                                  --all        Include all peripherals,
#                                                not just desk-like ones
#
#   connect [IDENTIFIER]          Connect and remember desk in
#                                  ~/.idasen.json.  If IDENTIFIER is
#                                  omitted, opens INTERACTIVE SELECTOR
#                                  (dialoguer Select with ColorfulTheme
#                                  showing discovered desks with RSSI).
#
#   down                          Move to configured minimum height
#                                  (default 0.0 cm above desk-min)
#
#   up                            Move to configured maximum height
#                                  (default 58.0 cm above desk-min)
#
#   move-to <HEIGHT>              Move to explicit height in cm
#                                  (e.g. `desk move-to 75.5`)
#
#   status                        Read current desk height
#
#   daemon                        (hidden — internal use) Run as JSON-
#                                  RPC daemon over Unix socket; other
#                                  `desk` invocations can talk to the
#                                  daemon for faster operation without
#                                  re-scanning BLE
#
# Persistent state:
#   ~/.idasen.json                Saved desk identifier + min/max
#                                  height config (JSON; created by
#                                  `desk connect`)
#
# Typical usage:
#   $ desk list                                   # show nearby desks
#   $ desk list --json | jq                       # machine-readable list
#   $ desk connect                                # interactive picker
#   $ desk connect IDASEN-AB-12-34                # explicit identifier
#   $ desk down                                   # move to sit-height
#   $ desk up                                     # move to stand-height
#   $ desk move-to 75                             # explicit height (cm)
#   $ desk status                                 # current height
#   $ desk daemon &                               # background daemon for
#                                                 # fast follow-up cmds
#
# BLE pairing:
#   The IDÅSEN desk does NOT require PIN-pairing; just `desk connect`
#   while the desk is powered on.  The desk advertises itself as
#   "Desk" or "IDASEN" — dialoguer's interactive selector filters BLE
#   results to "desk-like" by default (use --all to see everything).
#
# Permissions on Linux:
#   BLE scanning typically requires CAP_NET_ADMIN or running as root
#   on Linux.  Easier alternative: `sudo setcap cap_net_admin+eip
#   $(which desk)` to grant the capability.
#
# =============================================================================

_desk() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    local -a subcommands

    subcommands=(
        'list:list nearby desk-like BLE devices'
        'connect:connect and remember desk in ~/.idasen.json'
        'down:move to configured minimum height'
        'up:move to configured maximum height'
        'move-to:move to explicit height in cm'
        'status:read current desk height'
    )

    _arguments -C \
        '--timeout=[BLE scan time in seconds]:sec:' \
        '--connect-timeout=[connect/discover/read/write timeout]:sec:' \
        '(-v --verbose)'{-v,--verbose}'[verbose logs]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
        '--version[show version]' \
        '1: :->cmd' \
        '*::arg:->args' && ret=0

    case $state in
        (cmd)
            _describe -t commands 'desk command' subcommands && ret=0
            ;;
        (args)
            case $line[1] in
                (list)
                    _arguments \
                        '--json[output JSON]' \
                        '--all[include all peripherals, not just desks]' \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
                (connect)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:desk identifier:' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
                (move-to)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        '*:height in cm:' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
                (*)
                    _arguments \
                        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                        && ret=0
                    ;;
            esac
            ;;
    esac

    return ret
}

_desk "$@"
